Parnell: I wish my head could
forget what my eyes have seen

2
00:00:43,502 --> 00:00:45,630
in 32 years of firefighting.

3
00:00:51,260 --> 00:00:52,853
Interviewer: Why do you do this?

4
00:00:53,428 --> 00:00:53,519
Miller: We love...

5
00:00:54,054 --> 00:00:55,556
I love my job.

6
00:00:56,306 --> 00:01:02,234
It does... it's something
with adrenaline

7
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:04,781
that gets you pumped up (alarm).

8
00:01:05,357 --> 00:01:06,654
And here we go!

9
00:01:21,248 --> 00:01:23,342
Woman: (screams).

10
00:02:37,908 --> 00:02:40,627
Woman: Got to regroup, keep it
moving, that's the best I can do.

11
00:02:57,552 --> 00:03:02,353
Craig: That right there times
30 a night, times 30 years,

12
00:03:02,933 --> 00:03:10,863
is how you burn a city
down... one at a time.

13
00:03:22,994 --> 00:03:25,417
Man: It was probably the most
beautiful city back in the day,

14
00:03:25,706 --> 00:03:27,379
you know, when there was
factories everywhere,

15
00:03:27,666 --> 00:03:29,259
there was people spending
money around here.

16
00:03:29,543 --> 00:03:30,590
The car industry was booming.

17
00:03:31,169 --> 00:03:34,719
Man: It was much easier
to get a job and it was more

18
00:03:35,298 --> 00:03:36,550
of a family atmosphere then.

19
00:03:37,134 --> 00:03:38,477
You didn't have to lock your doors.

20
00:03:40,971 --> 00:03:42,018
Man: I grew up in Detroit.

21
00:03:42,889 --> 00:03:47,065
I've seen the City change from
a nice, decent neighborhood

22
00:03:47,644 --> 00:03:51,649
to certain areas that just
look like bombs have hit them.

23
00:03:57,028 --> 00:03:59,656
Man: Most of the neighborhoods
are blighted, vacant lots.

24
00:04:00,240 --> 00:04:01,412
Next to vacant dwellings.

25
00:04:02,367 --> 00:04:06,713
Parnell: We've got probably
one, two, three, four...

26
00:04:08,081 --> 00:04:13,383
six, seven, eight vacants
on my block.

27
00:04:14,337 --> 00:04:17,841
Dennis: It kind of hurts me to see
the City getting destroyed like this,

28
00:04:18,425 --> 00:04:20,393
I feel like I'm in the
burning of Rome sometime.

29
00:04:32,856 --> 00:04:33,448
Man: Population loss, I've
watched it go from a city

30
00:04:34,024 --> 00:04:36,698
of one-point-eight million
to seven-hundred thousand,

31
00:04:37,277 --> 00:04:39,621
leaves a lot of vacant homes.

32
00:04:40,197 --> 00:04:48,127
Man: The bottom line is everybody
that can seems to be ﬂeeing.

33
00:04:50,415 --> 00:04:54,545
Man: I mean, this has been
Katrina without the hurricane.

34
00:04:55,128 --> 00:04:56,630
Woman: Our city is
crumbling around us.

35
00:04:59,257 --> 00:05:02,261
Man: Imagine two-thirds of the
people in your city disappeared,

36
00:05:02,844 --> 00:05:05,518
but they left their houses,
their garbage, their furniture.

37
00:05:06,223 --> 00:05:07,224
Doogie: As long as
there's people leaving,

38
00:05:07,808 --> 00:05:10,357
as long as there's vacant
houses, there's going to be fires,

39
00:05:10,936 --> 00:05:15,032
it's called fire load,
there's more things to burn.

40
00:05:15,607 --> 00:05:18,201
Man: The neighborhood of our
district is, statistically,

41
00:05:18,777 --> 00:05:21,781
one of the worst places on
earth for crime, for poverty.

42
00:05:22,364 --> 00:05:23,661
Man: So they were shooting, too?

43
00:05:23,990 --> 00:05:24,115
Man: Came out right here.

44
00:05:24,699 --> 00:05:26,497
Woman: And the other
one was right there.

45
00:05:27,118 --> 00:05:29,871
Man: High murder rate,
high infant mortality rate.

46
00:05:31,456 --> 00:05:34,801
Reporter: Police telling me this is
not just a murder, but an execution.

47
00:05:35,377 --> 00:05:37,800
Man: Crimes that you never
would, in a million years,

48
00:05:38,380 --> 00:05:40,633
thought would happen
in your neighborhood.

49
00:05:46,388 --> 00:05:48,937
Woman: In the City of
Detroit last year alone,

50
00:05:49,516 --> 00:05:52,816
we had over 30,000 actual fire calls.

51
00:05:54,187 --> 00:05:57,657
I mean, we're in trouble,
we need help.

52
00:06:25,093 --> 00:06:26,060
Parnell: This don't have
nothing to do with the City,

53
00:06:26,636 --> 00:06:30,641
this is must my own
personal edge (alarm).

54
00:06:34,811 --> 00:06:40,489
My name is David
Parnell, I'm a FEO,

55
00:06:41,067 --> 00:06:42,910
Field Engine Operator,
for Engine Company 50.

56
00:06:43,486 --> 00:06:46,740
Craig: Dave Parnell and I
were hired about the same time,

57
00:06:47,324 --> 00:06:50,498
1977, great guy, solid guy.

58
00:06:51,077 --> 00:06:52,920
You feel safe when
he's behind the wheel.

59
00:06:53,496 --> 00:06:58,878
He'll get you water within 60
seconds of being on the fire drop.

60
00:06:59,461 --> 00:06:59,552
Parnell:That's my part.

61
00:07:00,128 --> 00:07:01,300
That's what I do.

62
