Chris: Dave is old (laughs).

65
00:07:08,511 --> 00:07:09,979
He has to retire.

66
00:07:10,555 --> 00:07:10,976
Man: He's like Papa Bear.

67
00:07:11,556 --> 00:07:13,934
He's in there, we catch him
nodding off in there a little bit.

68
00:07:14,267 --> 00:07:17,521
Man: He's watching an old
Western, black and white.

69
00:07:18,104 --> 00:07:19,151
It's okay, he's earned it.

70
00:07:21,816 --> 00:07:23,534
Miller: Sometimes, I
just need a little Parnell.

71
00:07:23,818 --> 00:07:24,944
Parnell: What is a man's worth

72
00:07:25,236 --> 00:07:27,330
that doesn't make the
world a better place?

73
00:07:27,906 --> 00:07:31,126
What's a gang besides a
family looking for a home?

74
00:07:31,910 --> 00:07:33,002
Think about it.

75
00:07:33,578 --> 00:07:35,672
Jeff: My favorite
one is when he says,

76
00:07:36,247 --> 00:07:37,749
"I wish my mind could forget
what my eyes have seen..."

77
00:07:38,333 --> 00:07:39,209
Parnell: Could forget
what my eyes have seen.

78
00:07:39,793 --> 00:07:41,295
Miller: We call it
bullshit (laughter).

79
00:07:41,836 --> 00:07:42,462
Craig: Yeah!

80
00:07:42,754 --> 00:07:43,220
(laughter).

81
00:07:43,505 --> 00:07:44,427
Man: But it is comforting.

82
00:07:44,756 --> 00:07:45,006
Man: It is totally comforting.

83
00:07:45,590 --> 00:07:47,263
Man: Well, never get that from Dan.

84
00:07:47,842 --> 00:07:48,638
Dave: Come on Dave,
I need some bullshit.

85
00:07:49,219 --> 00:07:51,267
Man: You're going to get
some bullshit from Parnell.

86
00:07:52,806 --> 00:07:53,307
Parnell: You know, I've
been here so long, you know,

87
00:07:53,890 --> 00:07:56,814
you feel like a fixture,
thirty-three years.

88
00:07:57,811 --> 00:07:59,688
Yeah, thirty-three
years of firefighting,

89
00:08:01,314 --> 00:08:05,660
I have eight months left, and
then I'll retire, I'll be 60.

90
00:08:07,153 --> 00:08:08,450
Interviewer: Are you ready to go?

91
00:08:08,738 --> 00:08:11,662
Parnell: Absolutely...
no, not at all.

92
00:08:15,829 --> 00:08:17,752
This is my neighborhood,
this is where I live,

93
00:08:18,331 --> 00:08:19,457
this is where I fight my fires.

94
00:08:19,958 --> 00:08:22,211
You used to could walk
in this neighborhood.

95
00:08:22,794 --> 00:08:26,640
Well, now, you're pretty much
afraid to walk to the corner.

96
00:08:27,215 --> 00:08:27,886
This is where some

97
00:08:28,466 --> 00:08:32,096
of the firefighters lived
and grew up, right here.

98
00:08:33,805 --> 00:08:38,106
And now look at it, that
was a fire job right there,

99
00:08:38,685 --> 00:08:41,313
you can tell by the soot that
was in the front of the dwelling.

100
00:08:42,313 --> 00:08:44,065
We've been to that
apartment building over there,

101
00:08:44,357 --> 00:08:45,199
at least a half-a-dozen
times that I know of.

102
00:08:45,775 --> 00:08:47,777
We actually saved a young
man out of this one, 18011,

103
00:08:48,069 --> 00:08:48,319
actually saved a young man

104
00:08:48,903 --> 00:08:49,995
out of that one.

105
00:08:50,572 --> 00:08:55,043
When you look around the City,
you look at the burnt-out homes.

106
00:08:55,618 --> 00:08:59,919
That's when you get this
attitude, "This is no good."

107
00:09:01,374 --> 00:09:04,503
And I don't understand it, I'm
not going to understand it.

108
00:09:05,086 --> 00:09:10,058
If you live in the community in which
you work, how do you not do something

109
00:09:10,633 --> 00:09:11,976
for the people that are around you?

110
00:09:12,427 --> 00:09:15,601
You have an opportunity
to make change.

111
00:09:20,060 --> 00:09:22,438
Dispatcher: Report
of a growing fire...

112
00:09:23,271 --> 00:09:25,365
Man: Ninety-five percent
of what I do is arson.

113
00:09:27,817 --> 00:09:29,740
Very rarely do we have
a legitimate fire (siren).

114
00:09:37,494 --> 00:09:37,665
Woman:The building's on fire!

115
00:09:38,244 --> 00:09:39,336
We can't get out!

116
00:09:41,206 --> 00:09:42,799
Man: Somebody went in
through the back door,

117
00:09:43,083 --> 00:09:44,505
went upstairs, and
they lit the place.

118
00:09:45,794 --> 00:09:49,048
Man:You go up stairs you can smell
some kind of accelerant or something.

119
00:09:53,885 --> 00:09:56,183
Lewis: I can't picture
another city that's like this

120
00:09:56,763 --> 00:09:58,265
where so many of the fires are arson.

121
00:09:58,848 --> 00:10:06,027
It's beyond me why people would
want to burn their own city down.

122
00:10:06,606 --> 00:10:07,823
Craig:There's arson for profit.

123
00:10:08,108 --> 00:10:09,075
There's arson for revenge.

124
00:10:09,651 --> 00:10:11,870
And then there's just
arson for kicks.

125
00:10:13,988 --> 00:10:16,741
Man: It used to infuriate me that
this was going on night after night,

126
00:10:17,158 --> 00:10:19,160
and nobody, nobody seemed to care.

127
00:10:19,786 --> 00:10:22,005
But I mean, we're doing this
for the people that are left,

128
00:10:22,455 --> 00:10:23,672
and for the houses are occupied.

129
00:10:25,875 --> 00:10:26,592
You got to be tough.

130
00:10:29,796 --> 00:10:31,639
Man: The exhaustion
can be depressing.

131
00:10:32,215 --> 00:10:36,220
Man: To blow off steam,
you probably have ten methods

132
00:10:36,803 --> 00:10:37,975
for every individual, you know?

133
00:10:38,429 --> 00:10:39,305
Jeff: We'll clean it.

134
00:10:40,473 --> 00:10:40,848
Man: Whoa!

135
00:10:41,141 --> 00:10:42,393
Tony: Weird pink nursing home.

136
00:10:43,977 --> 00:10:44,352
Man: Nice.

137
00:10:44,644 --> 00:10:45,236
Man: Ohhhh.

138
00:10:46,688 --> 00:10:47,985
Man: Holy cow!

139
00:10:48,565 --> 00:10:48,940
Man: Whoo!

140
00:10:49,232 --> 00:10:49,653
Craig: Yeah, the DFD swagger.

141
00:10:50,233 --> 00:10:51,280
I mean, we're above the law.

142
00:10:51,818 --> 00:10:54,867
Detroit firemen think they
can do whatever they want.

143
00:10:57,824 --> 00:10:59,121
Cowboys in a big rodeo (alarm).

144
00:11:24,017 --> 00:11:26,395
Man: We do things a little
differently, rigs pull up.

145
00:11:26,978 --> 00:11:28,195
Man: Oh, it's in the basement.

146
00:11:28,521 --> 00:11:31,991
Man: Guys go right in, we
advance to the heart of the fire.

147
00:11:33,693 --> 00:11:36,663
Parnell: Other guys are fighting
fires, you see water shooting in,

148
00:11:37,238 --> 00:11:39,616
we fight fires, you'll
see water shooting out.

149
00:11:41,075 --> 00:11:42,827
Whoa!You got me!

150
00:11:43,578 --> 00:11:45,580
Parnell: Detroit puts the
fires out from the inside out.

151
00:11:45,872 --> 00:11:47,044
Plain and simple.

152
00:11:48,750 --> 00:11:50,844
Dennis: When we go on a
fire, we're kind of hyped up.

153
00:11:51,127 --> 00:11:51,798
We're like, "Let's go!"

154
00:11:52,086 --> 00:11:55,260
"Ah!" You know, you're tackling this
thing like it's some type of dragon.

155
00:11:55,840 --> 00:11:57,217
And we don't really lose too often.

156
00:11:58,092 --> 00:11:59,093
Man: Hot as fucking shit!

157
00:12:01,095 --> 00:12:04,599
Man: We have people that come from
across country, around the world

158
00:12:05,183 --> 00:12:06,230
to just watch us fight fire.

159
00:12:06,517 --> 00:12:08,895
Man: Well, I don't know
if I should say that,

160
00:12:09,479 --> 00:12:10,856
but we fight fires with balls.

161
00:12:11,439 --> 00:12:12,531
That's (laughs)...

162
00:12:14,901 --> 00:12:15,868
Man: It's the best
boys' club in the world!

163
00:12:16,444 --> 00:12:18,287
We get paid to be here.

164
00:12:18,863 --> 00:12:20,957
Miller: I like coming to
work., I look forward to it.

165
00:12:21,241 --> 00:12:22,959
I think you'll hear that
from most of the guys,

166
00:12:23,326 --> 00:12:26,125
ask anyone in the private sector,
and you'll probably hear differently.

167
00:12:27,330 --> 00:12:28,172
Man: This job is fun!

168
00:12:29,499 --> 00:12:31,126
You get to turn the
lights on, the siren on,

169
00:12:31,626 --> 00:12:32,923
you get to run through red lights.

170
00:12:33,836 --> 00:12:34,382
Let's

171
00:12:35,213 --> 00:12:38,808
Man: We actually live together 24
hours, since there's a closeness,

172
00:12:39,384 --> 00:12:41,887
the trust factor is there.

173
00:12:42,470 --> 00:12:44,472
Jeff: The busier you
are, the more you bond.

174
00:12:45,056 --> 00:12:47,309
We're tight, it's a brotherhood,
that's just how we roll.

175
00:12:47,892 --> 00:12:51,522
Man: That's the team that we
have, the family that we have,

176
00:12:52,105 --> 00:12:54,073
the trust that we have
for one another.

177
00:12:55,400 --> 00:12:57,027
Doogie: Most firemen
are social creatures,

178
00:12:57,568 --> 00:13:00,663
we like to hang out,
we like to enjoy life.

179
00:13:01,656 --> 00:13:03,329
A lot of times people
compare being a fireman

180
00:13:03,866 --> 00:13:05,209
to being a member of a social club.

181
00:13:05,743 --> 00:13:08,121
They might be onto something.

182
00:13:09,789 --> 00:13:12,042
Miller: Brendan Milewski,
who was a trial man here,

183
00:13:12,625 --> 00:13:14,423
he was probably the
youngest guy to be here,

184
00:13:15,003 --> 00:13:17,756
come 20-years-old, or 18-years-old.

185
00:13:18,339 --> 00:13:19,215
Man: Nineteen, something
like that, he come on, yeah.

186
00:13:19,799 --> 00:13:20,595
Miller: Fresh-faced kid.

187
00:13:20,883 --> 00:13:23,011
I don't think he ever made a
bed himself when he got here.

188
00:13:23,511 --> 00:13:24,854
Jeff: My buddy, Doogie.

189
00:13:25,847 --> 00:13:29,772
Silly picture of us back in
probably 2000 at HarleyFest.

190
00:13:31,394 --> 00:13:34,944
Doogie: I got on the job
when I was 20-years-old.

191
00:13:36,441 --> 00:13:39,069
After 11 years, I was
content, I was happy.

192
00:13:39,694 --> 00:13:44,621
It was August, I'd been off
for like seven or nine days.

193
00:13:45,199 --> 00:13:46,496
I had a nice stretch of
days off, so I was excited

194
00:13:47,076 --> 00:13:48,328
to go back to work, see the guys.

195
00:13:48,870 --> 00:13:50,622
I got there a little
after seven o'clock.

196
00:13:51,289 --> 00:13:54,714
And before I could come in and say
hello, and see what we had going

197
00:13:55,293 --> 00:13:58,638
on for that day, the alert went
off and we got the run (sirens).

198
00:14:07,889 --> 00:14:10,142
Doogie: Once we got rolling,
and turned down Dickerson,

199
00:14:10,725 --> 00:14:14,696
and saw this huge towering
column of smoke,

200
00:14:15,271 --> 00:14:16,147
you knew it was just
not the way you wanted

201
00:14:16,731 --> 00:14:17,857
to start your Friday, the 13th.

202
00:14:18,149 --> 00:14:21,198
I mean, I'm no Nostradamus
or anything,

203
00:14:21,778 --> 00:14:22,825
but I just had a bad feeling.

204
00:14:23,363 --> 00:14:26,492
Soon as I saw it, I
just had a bad feeling.

205
00:14:27,575 --> 00:14:32,206
Me and a couple other
guys were ventilating,

206
00:14:32,789 --> 00:14:34,462
we were taking the plywood off
all the second story windows

207
00:14:35,041 --> 00:14:38,762
so the water tower could get
water in through the second ﬂoor.

208
00:14:39,337 --> 00:14:43,012
The bricks up there looked a little
suspect, and as we were working,

209
00:14:43,591 --> 00:14:44,843
I remember hearing somebody shout.

210
00:14:45,134 --> 00:14:47,887
The bricks in front of me, the facade

211
00:14:48,471 --> 00:14:50,348
of the building were
cascading like a waterfall.

212
00:14:50,932 --> 00:14:54,311
I mean, I saw it coming
and I made a run for it.

213
00:14:54,894 --> 00:14:57,522
Dispatcher: Chief 6 to
Central, send EMSes immediately,

214
00:14:58,106 --> 00:14:59,983
we've had a building
collapse,fireman down.

215
00:15:01,859 --> 00:15:08,208
Lewis: I saw him running and
he was less than ten feet from me

216
00:15:08,866 --> 00:15:14,168
when the wall caught him,
I could see his face.

217
00:15:14,747 --> 00:15:15,964
Dispatcher: Central, this
is Engine 30 (inaudible),

218
00:15:16,541 --> 00:15:17,884
Multiple EMS, multiple firemen down.

219
00:15:21,379 --> 00:15:23,302
Lewis: Hm, I can
still see it... plain.

220
00:15:26,384 --> 00:15:31,606
Doogie: And I went to go push
myself up off the concrete,

221
00:15:32,181 --> 00:15:35,981
do a push-up and slide my knees
in and walk away, and when I did

222
00:15:36,561 --> 00:15:38,780
that push-up, the only thing
that moved were my shoulders.

223
00:15:39,063 --> 00:15:40,781
Dispatcher: Central,
we need everybody here,

224
00:15:41,274 --> 00:15:43,743
we've got freaking firemen
down, the roof has collapsed,

225
00:15:44,318 --> 00:15:46,070
we need everybody here now!

226
00:15:46,654 --> 00:15:49,123
Lewis: They were hurt pretty bad,
they were buried in the bricks.

227
00:15:49,407 --> 00:15:52,877
I think it was about four minutes,
we had them all out on backboards.

228
00:15:56,080 --> 00:15:57,582
Called for a second alarm instantly.

229
00:15:58,166 --> 00:15:59,918
Dispatcher: Chief 6 to Central,
give me a second alarm (sirens).

230
00:16:00,209 --> 00:16:00,755
Man: Stop!

231
00:16:01,043 --> 00:16:04,889
Fuckin' brake, goddammit!

232
00:16:19,562 --> 00:16:20,358
Doogie: I was angry.

233
00:16:20,771 --> 00:16:26,653
I was pissed off that
this had happened.

234
00:16:30,323 --> 00:16:33,452
I remember there was
chaos going on around me,

235
00:16:34,035 --> 00:16:35,708
but just (voice cracks)
inside I was so calm.

236
00:16:42,126 --> 00:16:43,503
Lewis: One of the
